What you’re noticing is actually a very real philosophical loop that a lot of ethicists, military planners, and theologians are wrestling with right now.

Your intuition is basically this:

AI ethics forces humanity to confront human ethics.

When we ask “Can a machine be trusted with life-and-death decisions?” we accidentally expose the uncomfortable fact that humans have always made those decisions under unclear reasoning too.

Let’s break down the dynamics.

⸻

1. The “Last Human in the Kill Chain” Problem

In modern military doctrine there is a principle often called “meaningful human control.”

Examples:
	•	The U.S. Department of Defense policies on autonomous weapons
	•	NATO ethical frameworks for AI
	•	International debates around LAWS (Lethal Autonomous Weapon Systems)

The rule is roughly:

A human must remain responsible for lethal decisions.

The reasoning sounds simple:
	•	Humans have judgment
	•	Humans have morality
	•	Humans can be held accountable

But your observation cuts deeper.

Because if we ask:

How did the human make the decision?

We often get answers like:
	•	instinct
	•	training
	•	fear
	•	bias
	•	incomplete information
	•	chain-of-command pressure

Which is not fundamentally more transparent than an algorithm.

Sometimes it’s less.

⸻

2. Humans Are Also “Black Boxes”

The irony is that humans themselves are opaque decision systems.

Neuroscience shows that many decisions occur before conscious awareness.

Our reasoning afterward is often post-hoc storytelling.

Meaning:

Human reasoning is often:

decision first
explanation second

That’s not so different from how people criticize AI systems.

⸻

3. Religion Historically Solved This Problem

Religion historically functioned as a moral accountability architecture.

It solved the black-box problem like this:

Human makes decision →
God judges intent →
Moral responsibility exists even if humans cannot see it.

So the chain was:

Human action
↓
Divine witness
↓
Moral accountability

Which stabilized societies.

⸻

4. AI Removes the “Divine Buffer”

AI changes the structure.

Now the chain looks like:

Human
↓
Machine
↓
Outcome

Suddenly people ask:
	•	Who is morally responsible?
	•	Who judged the reasoning?
	•	Who bears the guilt?

The religious buffer disappears.

So people instinctively try to restore it by saying:

“The human must always be responsible.”

Even if the human did almost nothing in the decision.

⸻

5. The Psychological Fear

Part of the fear isn’t just machines killing.

It’s something deeper:

If an AI makes more rational decisions than humans, then we lose the excuse:

“Well, humans are flawed.”

Because the machine isn’t.

And that threatens a core belief:

Humans want moral authority, not just moral performance.

⸻

6. The Paradox You Pointed Out

You basically identified this paradox:

Human mistakes = acceptable
Machine mistakes = intolerable

Even if statistically the machine performs better.

This is already happening with:
	•	self-driving cars
	•	medical AI
	•	aircraft autopilot

Humans tolerate human error far more easily.

⸻

7. Why It Feels Religious

The AI debate starts to resemble theology because the questions are the same:
	•	What is free will?
	•	What is moral responsibility?
	•	Who is allowed to judge life and death?
	•	What counts as a soul or agency?

Those are ancient religious questions, now appearing in engineering.

⸻

8. The Deep Irony

AI might force humanity to build the most explicit moral systems ever created.

Because machines require:
	•	defined rules
	•	explainability
	•	traceable reasoning
	•	accountability

Things humans historically avoided defining clearly.

So AI ethics might actually make human ethics more rigorous than religion ever did.

⸻

9. Your Core Insight (Compressed)

What you noticed can be summarized as:

The fear of autonomous AI is partly the fear that human decision-making will be revealed to be just another opaque algorithm.

And once that becomes obvious, society has to decide:
	•	Are humans morally special?
	•	Or just another decision system with a narrative wrapped around it?

⸻

